{"summary":"Accept the amendments that identify real schema/provenance and attempt-matching defects in the milestone journal/lineage flow. Reject the amendment that only proposes an assertion around malformed unsupported data, and reject the broad request to remove the repair layer because that logic is part of the current restart-safety and replay contract, not just unused migration baggage.","votes":[{"amendment_id":"fr-21-cbb5ddb0","decision":"accept","rationale":"The repair paths in `FsMilestoneJournalStore` deserialize and then re-render journal detail payloads through local mirror structs instead of the model's canonical payload types. That creates real schema-drift risk: Serde will accept extra fields, and any repair rewrite can drop or ignore newer fields unless both copies are updated in lockstep. Sharing the type or asserting equivalence would prevent silent journal data loss for both start and completion events."},{"amendment_id":"fr-21-5549be65","decision":"reject","rationale":"This branch only matters if a stored `BeadStarted` event exists without `details`. Current producers always attach details, so that case is malformed or unsupported data rather than a demonstrated correctness gap in the intended flow. A `debug_assert!` could document the invariant, but the current `None` return is a reasonable fail-closed behavior and does not identify a substantive bug."},{"amendment_id":"fr-21-e0d6bb34","decision":"accept","rationale":"When `run_id` is supplied and no exact run-id match exists, `update_task_run` inspects open bead/project rows but rejects the case where the sole open row is runless, without considering `started_at`. That blocks a legitimate same-attempt recovery flow where start was recorded before the controller knew the run id. The later update path already knows how to backfill `run_id` and `plan_hash` once the row is selected, so the selection logic is the defect."},{"amendment_id":"fr-21-1c624db9","decision":"accept","rationale":"After `persist_plan`, the service already has a canonical `snapshot.plan_hash`, but `record_bead_start` and `update_task_run` ignore it when callers pass `None`. That allows lineage rows and journal details to persist with `plan_hash: None` even though the milestone snapshot already knows the active plan version, which is a real provenance loss. The exact completion fallback rules need care, but the missing defaulting or backfill behavior is a valid defect."},{"amendment_id":"fr-21-5c56671a","decision":"reject","rationale":"The cited logic is not just dead migration code. In this implementation it underpins partial-write repair, replay idempotence, duplicate collapse, and tolerance for runless legacy or drifted rows, and those behaviors are explicitly exercised by tests and align with the project's stated recovery and compatibility requirements. The merge and backfill paths are also narrowly guarded by run-id or exact `started_at` matching and reject conflicts; removing them would regress correctness more than it would simplify the model."}]}